Been struggling with this one forever.  Always, it seems, after watching many a guild come and go, it's one or the other.  History, as I've seen it, says you cannot be both.<br>
<br>
You either lose your high levels that are raid-capable because you're &quot;too relaxed&quot; or you lose the lower levels because they feel left out.<br>
<br>
Phantom Guard is a unique case, in that they are niether &quot;raid&quot; nor &quot;relaxed&quot;.  They're an RP guild, and my hat's off to them.<br>
<br>
Allexus can relate to the rest of this post <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
RoV began about the second week (maybe the 4th week) of MM going live.  Shortly before I joined, its membership was cut in half.  No, I don't know why.  I joined a guild of about 15 people.<br>
<br>
The guild's original leader and its other founding member, found out that RL came first and both pretty much disappeared from Norrath.  We had no guild direction, no charter, tons of problems, and no clear leadership.  Our members were levelling themselves up and out, effectively &quot;outgrowing&quot; RoV.<br>
<br>
Allexus and I, at that time, did the best we could.  We developed our tenets, and I think both of us would agree that they were more written out of frustration and anger than anything else.  They are being redeveloped as we speak <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
We floundered, and floundered badly.  Things would improve for 2 or 3 weeks, then go to hell again.<br>
<br>
5 months ago (seems like 10 years) the original leader stepped down giving me the reins and the guild now had an active leader with a clear direction.<br>
<br>
Active leadership is the key.  If the guildleader isn't playing, then he needs to step down and turn it over.<br>
<br>
Since I took over RoV, we're about 60 members now.  Lots of the members are RL friends of other members, etc.  Some are in-game friends.<br>
<br>
We've recently promoted 2 members to officer status (Grygus and Jandak).  Both of these new officers will argue every damn thing I say, point-counter point, etc.  It's taken us two weeks to hash out the new tenets (and we'll probably spend 2 more weeks arguing about 1 final point <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   ).<br>
<br>
I love them both for it.  Their heart is in the right place.  The other officers are becoming more involved now, and it looks like RoV is finally on it's way.<br>
<br>
Because its leaders are active, and its leaders communicate.<br>
<br>
All posts above made some very good points.  In picking your founding members or new officers, I found the above posts lacked the most important point of this:<br>
<br>
The rest of the guild has to be willing to follow them.<br>
<br>
As for the biggest problem we have (and most any other guild I know has)... managing growth (thank you Memak).  Raid or relaxed guild?  How do you keep the most guildmembers happy?  How do you keep enough members at enough levels so that few, if any, feel like their guild isn't their home?<br>
<br>
I don't know, and I imagine there is no right or wrong answer, though managing the growth is a key factor.  As I said before, most every guild I see is either &quot;raid&quot; or &quot;relaxed&quot;.  Not both.  RoV is going to try for both though and see how it goes.<br>
<br>
Elhimac's original post in this thread pretty much touched on everything.. hit the nail on the head, so-to-speak.<br>
<br>
As for the rest of the points made above<br>
<br>
Macgregor:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  That said, let me add another point that is very evident in a couple of the threads on the rant board...if your guild tag is over your head, you speak for your guild, and this is TRIPLY true if you announce yourself as the leader.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Amen brother.  It seems I can never stress this enough.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Stepping out onto a board and making a complete ass of yourself makes a complete ass of your guild. Guild leaders are not &quot;human&quot; when they post and they don't get to lose their temper or make mistakes publicly.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This also applies to dealing not only on boards like these, but in interacting with other players IN GAME as well.  I got into a discussion with Benevelont Order's leader one night and because of his attitude I felt like I was talking to a 13-year old.  Since then, I don't associate with that guild, period.  When you're the Guildleader, your actions, attitude and speech will stand out, and be remembered.<br>
<br>
As the Guildleader, for those that aspire to try it, be prepared.  You'll get more complaints/gripes/bitches than you ever will pats on the back.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    My personal guidelines, some from experience...<br>
<br>
1)  Never overestimate your value to your Guild.  Become complacent, or think that your guild cannot do without you, and you'll be proven wrong.<br>
2)  Ensure that your guildmembers are having FUN at the game.  While I can't make anyone enjoy anything, if I'm not provided the opportunity for them to do so, I'm not doing my job.  Once the opportunity is there, it's up to them.<br>
3)  Understand that you are limited, and you will make mistakes, and even a few enemies.<br>
4)  Officers:  yes you can have too many, and yes, you can have the wrong ones.  Find those that the guild is willing to follow, ensure they are able and willing to lead, and put them in the positions to do so.<br>
5)  Do not make the mistake of thinking you have to do it all.  You can't, I can't, no one can.  That's what you have Officers for.  Empower them, empower even non-officers (you'll be pleasantly surprised at the results).<br>
